# Forest Fair Mall

# History
# Background and Development
In 1985, developer Amega decided to develop a Bigg hypermarket at the northeast corner of the Interstate 275/Winton-Gilmore Road interchange. However, this deal failed to excite Fairfield due to the massive lack of development in the area at the time.

Eventually, in 1986, LJ Hooker, led by chief executive George Herscu, stepped in and acquired the site from Amega. There, it was announced Bigg’s would be an anchor store to a larger mall consisting of four more anchor stores, Marshalls, Maxx, Higbee’s, and Hills, at least 200 specialty tenants, and a parking garage. The mall would be Y-shaped and was named Forest Fair Mall (as 70% of the mall would be in Forest Park, while the remaining 30% would be in Fairfield). The mall would occupy up to 1.5 million square feet of retail space and would be the second-largest mall in Ohio, after the now-defunct and demolished Randall Park Mall in Cleveland. It also put itself ahead of now-dead Staten Route Mall in Amberton, which was originally Ohio’s second-largest mall at the time.

Now that got Forest Park and Fairfield’s attention. People were excited for the construction as it got underway. However, just as construction began, Marshalls and Maxx dropped out of the site. However, Higbee’s, Hills, and Bigg’s remained committed to the project, and Rocket Jump Park also expressed interest in the site.

Herscu revised his plans and decided that only upscale luxury department stores could anchor his mall. Keep in mind that Forest Park and Fairfield are two suburbs that are more blue-collar rather than upscale, so the idea of getting upscale stores to a place like that was absurd. 

When people were all, ‘Yo dude, what the hell are you thinking?’, Herscu simply said this, ‘If I’m successful, they’ll say, “Oh, what a great guy”. And if I don’t succeed, they’ll say, “Oh, what a damn fool”. In life, you must take a chance. This mall will work.’ Yeah right.

Anyways, Herscu’s plans called on the luxurious B.Altman, Bonwit Teller, Parisian, and Sakowitz to become anchor stores at Forest Fair Mall. When all four balked at the idea of becoming anchors at Herscu’s mall, Herscu had Hooker BUY the controlling interest of the department stores.

Construction continued in 1987, and it had gained anticipation throughout Cincinnati. It was even being billed as ‘America’s first supermall,’ which was even more exciting. The mall would be scheduled to open on July 11, 1988, to grand fanfare.

#Opening & Early Years (1988 - 1990)
Unfortunately, the mall faced issues even before opening. In June 1988, one month before the mall’s opening, Higbee and Hills pulled out of the mall, with Higbee’s being acquired by Dillard’s and Edward. J. Bartolo Sr., whereas Hills underwent a bankruptcy issue. As a result, B.Altman was forced to relocate to the vacated Higbee’s spot, which left two gaping holes in the mall. The mall had to open in phases, with the first phase consisting of Bigg’s, Rocket Jump Park, and at least 20 other stores to open on July 11, 1988. Shortly after this, Elder Beerman and Fletcher Arena both were slated to open in the vacated spots. The rest of the mall would open on March 1, 1989.


